metadata.name: Wordflow #120
metadata.description:
Visualizing variations of a paragraph about writing, structured as a binary tree, authored collaboratively with custom AI, and (painstakingly) handwritten.

Vector animation made by manipulating raw SVG code in vanilla JS, with motion based on an algorithm I first explored in the following dweet: dwitter.net/d/5107

The compositions extend far past the boundaries of your screen, but you'll be able to see a complete view in any SVG viewer or editor:

Press `s` (on mobile: long swipe down) to save current view to SVG file.

Press `r` (on mobile: long swipe up) to toggle reading mode, which will show each handwritten line in order, with fixed size and position.

Double click (on mobile: double tap) to show or hide the color palette extraction menu.

For color palettes, each token makes (optional) use of your webcam as well as any images you may wish to insert. (Please note that no images or video will be saved or sent anywhere, as all processing occurs locally on your machine.)

I had originally planned to use my own color palette extraction algorithm, as I wrote one myself a while back, but then I discovered Lokesh Dhakar's wonderful open source "Color Thief" JS library (github.com/lokesh/color-thief), which does a better (and quicker) job, and so it became this project's sole dependency.

rossgoodwin.com

attributes.name: Complete text
attributes.value: Words flow from the meaning like metal shavings from the grinding wheel. Purling, swarming, bright and intricate like webs of light, phosphenes. The same patterns reoccurring, a mandala, a quartz crystal in the sun. The meaning grabs back at them, but they are quicker, more nimble, and woven together in a thousand interlocking facets that enclose and control the original core.

metadata.name: <iframes> #4
metadata.description:
The <iframe> HTML element is an element that allows a web document to embed the contents of another web document within itself. iframes are at the core of fxhash. They are portals opening our view to rich content.

This work is a portal to itself. It loads itself within itself 20 times. It's not pretty, it reminds us of WordArt, it's a little bit hacky, it might break when our tools to display HTML will change. But it's a proof that the limits of our tools are only limits until creativity breaks them.

This work is not purely deterministic, because it simply cannot be. Slight timing differences due to loading times being different each time an <iframe> is loaded will make each visualization slightly unique.

If you view this token on mobile, the nesting limit was reduced to 4 to prevent performance issues.

This work is highly experimental. It leverages a "hack" to allow iframes to be nested.
Firefox max <iframe> nesting depth as of 28/12/2021 is capped at 9.
Works with chrome desktop 96.0.4664.110

metadata.name: The Three-Body Problem #59
metadata.description:
The Three-Body Problem refers to the difficulty in evaluating an analytical expression for an object under the influence of two massive bodies. This work shows the gravitational vector field from two such bodies. Occasionally, lines will also show curves of equipotential in this field, the centre of mass of the system, the orbital paths traced out. The system is periodic and will loop forever.

Press UP to export one second of frames, and DOWN to save an SVG from the current frame.

metadata.name: THE400FLIPS #61
metadata.description:
The more they flip. The more you’ll make.

p5.js –> Blockchain


Controls:

[s] save as PNG.
[a] render alternate higher resolution artwork (takes a few seconds).
[z] save alternate artwork as PNG.


Artist note:

Primary royalties are split 95-5% between artist and The Processing Foundation.

Secondary royalties go to the minters (99.9% of the 15%).

The preview thumbnails don’t do justice to the artworks. Please run the code to appreciate them better. Also, remember to check the alternate higher resolution renders using [a].

Some preview thumbnails might look slightly different to the artwork seen when running the code. This is due to the resolution difference between the capture module and the live code on your device. 

Please get in touch in the event of a blank preview thumbnail. 

Made in p5.js and rendered in webGL. Tested on Chrome and Safari.

metadata.name: Shapes on a Plane #444
metadata.description:
“Shapes on a Plane” explores imaginary structures and worlds through simple shapes. It’s intended for small-scale print.

As a kid I was obsessed with Lego, Duplo, wooden building blocks... anything I could make something with.

I’d spend hours building things, imagining new worlds, new machines, new concepts, then i’d take them apart and create a whole new idea to explore.

To me, this piece to me is a reminder of that time - many days spent exploring ideas with those simple objects - no care for viability, for marketability, for audiences or business. Just pure fun.

Without this time in my life, I doubt I’d have found my passion for creating in the way I do today.

metadata.name: PixlFlippr #495
metadata.description:
PixlFlippr is an offshoot of my "Simple Harmonic Motion" series, inspired by the complexity of life emerging through the interaction of simple 'dumb' behaviors, with intricate details emerging on multiple scales. PixlFlippr operates on a pixel level (in the form of a GLSL frag shader).

Every pixel oscillates at a single fixed frequency, slightly out-of-sync with its neighbors. There is no explicit pixel-neighborhood communication (as there would be in eg Cellular Automata), and every pixel acts autonomously, oblivious to its surroundings. Yet collectively, the entire system exhibits constantly evolving complex high level behavior on many scales, ranging from patterns & behaviors spanning a few pixels, all the way up to the level of the entire image. These are further amplified through the emergent pixel aliasing artefacts & moiré patterns. 

Also, it's trippy af. 

PS All generative mints are a seamless loop with a loop duration ranging from a few minutes to over an hour. So stick around & watch it mutate!

metadata.name: Quantum Vacuum #613
metadata.description:
Empty space is not empty. It's filled with energy, transient fluctuations in quantum fields, bubbling with virtual particles popping in and out of existence. 

Part of an ongoing series of work combining my fascination with the fringes of fundamental physics, the emergence of complex behaviour through the interaction of very simple rules, and my obsession with hacking our perceptual systems. 

/Disclaimer: This is not a simulation, but an artistic conceptual interpretation and dramatization. :)
